Part 8

Reddy came to the house himself this time. He wasn't summoned by any boardroom schedule, and he carried a blue folder that he kept patting with his hand as if it might run away from him.

Binay received him in the small sitting room off his bedroom, the one with the single good leather chair reserved for visitors. The old man was thinner now than even the board meeting had shown, but he was alert and sharp-eyed, waving off the private nurse who hovered near the doorway.

"Binay saab," Reddy said, sitting down. He opened the folder on his knees, then seemed to forget the numbers entirely and just spoke. "Seven hundred crore. That is what the liquor division was doing when your son took over the South expansion. This year, it has crossed fourteen hundred crore."

Binay's eyebrows lifted slightly. That was the whole of his reaction, but it seemed to satisfy Reddy more than a long speech would have.

Pradhan-babu, who had been standing near the doorway to refill the water glass, set the jug down on the console table and said nothing. He had worked for Binay Ahuja for thirty-one years and had never heard a crore figure that size said aloud in this room. He stood very still for a moment, then quietly refilled the glass and went back to his desk.

"South alone has brought six hundred crore," Reddy continued, pointing at the chart. "Manufactured there, and now exported worldwide. Nobody on the board thought a first-time entrant would touch international distribution this fast. We are already scouting land for two more plants. If this holds, the company touches ten thousand crore within five years."

"You were the one who called him a kid in front of the others," Binay said, not unkindly, watching Reddy's face carefully.

"I was," Reddy said, not looking away from his gaze. "And I will say it again if I am ever wrong about someone else. But I was wrong about this one."

Vikram stood near the window through all of this, saying very little. It was the way he had learned to stand in most rooms that discussed him rather than spoke to him.

When Reddy rose to leave, he crossed the room and rested his hand briefly on Vikram's shoulder. It wasn't a formal handshake or a congratulatory speech; it was just a hand, there for a second and gone, the kind of gesture older men give when they have run out of better ways to say something.

Vikram felt something loosen in his chest that he hadn't realized was tight.

---

He stood at the window for a long time after Reddy's car had pulled away, watching the iron gate close slowly behind the tail-lights. He found that the warmth of the moment faded much faster than he expected it to.

Fourteen hundred crore. Ten thousand crore in five years. 

These were numbers that would have meant everything to him once, when he was in a hostel room, imagining a life entirely different from this one.

But he didn't feel any great triumph. He felt something closer to a duty discharged than a dream fulfilled. Like finishing a borrowed book he had never quite wanted to read, but had carried too long to return unfinished.

Liquor had been his father's calling, not his. He had carried it forward because someone had to, because the alternative was letting Binay's life's work collapse under a medical diagnosis that nobody could argue with anymore.

Somewhere underneath the fourteen hundred crore, a much smaller, much older thought kept surfacing, uninvited, like a seed in the wind: *what would I have built, if I had been building for myself instead of for him?*

He did not know the answer to that question yet. He wasn't even sure, standing at that window in the dark, that he was supposed to be looking for one.

---

Reddy chose Grand Regency in Hyderabad for dinner. The kind of restaurant where serious things are discussed in settings so comfortable that nothing has to feel serious.

He had asked Vikram with the specific formality of a man who has something to say and has chosen the most expensive possible container in which to say it.

First whiskey: with the starters. Second: as the main course arrived. Third: during a gap in the conversation that Reddy filled by looking at the tablecloth, then the ceiling, then his glass.

"I was wrong about you," Reddy said.

Vikram waited.

"When you first came to Nandyal. I thought you were a Calcutta boy. Money but no sense. The kind who comes for six months, causes problems, goes home." He paused. "I was wrong. You stayed. You dealt with the municipality. You fixed the water line yourself when they cut it. That is not something a Calcutta boy does. That is something a man does."

He drank.

The fourth whiskey arrived.

"The thing about you, Vikram," Reddy said, leaning slightly forward, his voice the voice of a man arriving at a sentence he had been building toward all evening, "is that you never—"

He stopped. His chin dropped. His eyes closed. His breathing changed.

He was asleep.

Not dramatically. Just the quiet subsidence of a man whose body had been waiting for a pause in the conversation and taken it. His hand remained on the glass.

Vikram called Reddy's driver. He paid both covers — the wine, the whiskey, the four courses — without reviewing the bill. He went back to his hotel.

He never found out how the sentence ended.

Over the years — in the factory office, in the courtyard in Bagbazar, in the hospital corridor much later — the sentence surfaced occasionally: *the thing about you, Vikram, is that you never—*

He had guesses. Several candidates. He tried each of them at different times. None felt precisely right. He thought, more than once, that the unfinished sentence was more accurate than any of the finished versions he had constructed for it. That the truth about a person is more often contained in the pause before the words than in the words themselves.

Reddy never finished it. By the following morning he had no memory of beginning it.

